<div id="review_2889836552" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2889836552" />
    <a title="Emily" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5567574-emily"><img alt="Emily" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1347390065p2/5567574.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2889836552?book_show_action=true">Jul 09, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Emily" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Emily" href="/user/show/5567574-emily">Emily</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5567574-emily?shelf=childrens-books">childrens-books</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2889836552" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5379436045260496381">I&apos;ve loved the other Brambly Hedge books that I&apos;ve read so far, but this one struck two wrong notes with me: <br/><a class='jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction'>(view spoiler)</a><span class='spoilerContainer' style='display: none'>[<br/>One, the concept of a secret staircase and hidden rooms that no one knows about but are completely stocked as if someone had just stopped living there abruptly. As an adult reader, I can&apos;t help but wonder what happened. Did they just lose the key generations ago? But doors can be broken down. Did they shut it all up for a reason? Without a backstory explaining it, I&apos;m prone</span></span>
  <span id="freeText5379436045260496381" style="display:none">I've loved the other Brambly Hedge books that I've read so far, but this one struck two wrong notes with me: <br /><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[<br />One, the concept of a secret staircase and hidden rooms that no one knows about but are completely stocked as if someone had just stopped living there abruptly. As an adult reader, I can't help but wonder what happened. Did they just lose the key generations ago? But doors can be broken down. Did they shut it all up for a reason? Without a backstory explaining it, I'm prone to assume something dark or depressing. Nothing in the presentation of the pictures or wording was dark, so a young child would probably not be disturbed by any of that, but I was. <br /><br />Two, the story ends with the young mice keeping their discovery secret from the older mice. Many of my favorite stories from my childhood involve some sort of secret place that the children discover and is kept hidden from the adults but in those either 1) something bad happens and the adults come find the children (Mandy), 2) the children end up telling the adults (The Secret Garden, The Lion, the Witch and the Wardrobe), or 3) the events are fantastical (more so than just anthropomorphized animals) and so there is a degree of separation of reality from the story (The Castle in the Attic, Five Children and It). Is it just because I'm a parent now and scared by the potential danger of secrets? Maybe. But there does seem to be something different in the way this secret place is handled. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span></span>
  <a data-text-id="5379436045260496381" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


